Found the bug! The strings are being read as `"433"` PLUS the 4-byte length prefix. So the actual string contains the binary length bytes too.

Look at the output:
- `pdes=' 433'` (with leading space) — actually that's the 4-byte length prefix `3, 0, 0, 0` (which is 3 in little-endian = the length of "433" which is 3 bytes)
- `full='   433 Eros (A898 PA)'` — the prefix is the length of the full name

So my `readOne` function is reading `len` bytes of the prefix AND the string. The makeStringReader in my code uses:
```ts
const start = offsets[idx] + base;
const end = offsets[idx + 1] + base;
const len = end - start;
```

But the offsets include the 4-byte prefix. So the substring INCLUDES the prefix bytes.

Looking at packStringTable:
```js
let off = 0;
for (let i = 0; i < enc.length; i++) {
  offsets[i] = off;  // start of this entry, INCLUDING the 4-byte length prefix
  // write length prefix
  out[off] = enc[i].length & 0xff;
  // ...
  off += 4;
  out.set(enc[i], off);
  off += enc[i].length;
}
offsets[enc.length] = off;
```

So `offsets[i]` = start of i-th entry (including 4-byte prefix). `offsets[i+1]` = start of next entry (or end of last).

So `end - start = 4 + string_length`. My reader decodes ALL of it (prefix + string).

The fix is to skip the first 4 bytes of the entry:
```ts
const start = offsets[idx] + base + 4;  // skip 4-byte length prefix
const end = offsets[idx + 1] + base;
```

Or remove the length prefix entirely (since we have offsets for delimiting entries) — that's cleaner.

Let me fix the preprocess script to NOT include the length prefix (offsets already delimit entries), and update the reader to match.

